{code}

h3. Issue Summary

When making an API call to obtain the list of projects on account:

 [https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/teams/%7Busername%7D/projects/#get]

[https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/teams/Account-Name/projects/]

the response you are getting to the path to obtain the list of repositories in each project returns the path in the following format:

 
{code:java}
"repositories": {

"href": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/account-name?q='project.key="NewPTst"'"{code}
 
 if you try to use the returned URI to obtain the list of repositories in the project, our API will respond with an error 
{code:java}
"type": "error", "error": { "message": "Invalid filter query expression: Illegal character in input: ''project.key="NewPTst"'', line: 1, error" }{code}
 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # run the GET API call to obtain list of project on an account, example:  [https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/teams/account-name/projects/]
 # In the returned results , to obtain the list the repositories path is returned in incorrect format, as listed above and using that URI will return an error. 

h3. Expected Results

in the returned results to obtain the list of repositories in that project, we should return a valid URL that customer doesn't have to modify or adjust to get results.
h3. Actual Results

Listed above error msg 
{code:java}
"type": "error", "error": { "message": "Invalid filter query expression: Illegal character in input: ''project.key="NewPTst"'', line: 1, error" }{code}
h3. Workaround

The workaround to make the call work, you have to adjust that URI for repositories to the following format: 
{code:java}
https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/account-name?q=project.key="NewPTst"{code}
so the user will need to remove the ' ' around the value of the `q` parameter. Do not remove the `q` parameter as this is how the results will be filtered by the correct project key. For more information about filtering in APIs, see [Bitbucket API - Filter and sort API objects|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/meta/filtering].

When attempting to use Git locally against Bitbucket, if an account is org managed, it's not possible to use your SSO password, as you get an error like the one below:
{code}
fatal: Authentication failed for 'https://<username>@bitbucket.org/<repoSlug>
{code}

In this case, you would have to use either an app password or an SSH key to proceed with the authentication attempt, as a workaround.

However, this feature request is to add the ability to use your SSO password for authentication locally.
